this life, right here, #rightnow you have the power to #live inside as well as outside and you have the #power to allow yourself to quite, to give up, to continue to be a victim instead of a survivor, it is your free #will that you allow to fester and and grow....#life or #death so #getup and #getmoving 
your beautiful life is waiting! 
#rachelwolchin
#die #death

text:
hello, world!

my father just passed away so no fun and games for me me me anymore, for a while. everything is ok - this was just as expected as the last big one for me, almost three years ago. nudge nudge, wink wink.

i want to thank everyone for the support on this pretty unfantastic voyage from nowhere to nothing. i don't know if me me me - or rather we, the liddle earthlings - achieved anything. personally it's absolutly nothing to me me me, this was never about my real desires.

i tried to try my best and this was the best i got. despite being a tiny finnish quarter pounder i am also just a human being with me me me own businesses -  totally unrelated to michael cohen - to run, especially now.

you can use the information provided below as you want. please note that i might have commited some copyright violations, though.

happy holidays - during these blasphemous times there is really no reason to talk about christmas. it's only irony eternally repeating itself that it's the hypocritical and immoral judeo-christian church militant that is killing the common god this time - they just couldn't wait for ai to do the job, could they?

all the best from finland, stay safe and take care!

text:
hello, world!

my father just passed away so no fun and games for me me me anymore, for a while. everything is ok - this was just as expected as the last big one for me, almost three years ago. nudge nudge, wink wink.

i want to thank everyone for the support on this pretty unfantastic voyage from nowhere to nothing. i don't know if me me me - or rather we, the liddle earthlings - achieved anything. personally it's absolutly nothing to me me me, this was never about my real desires.

i tried to try my best and this was the best i got. despite being a tiny finnish quarter pounder i am also just a human being with me me me own businesses -  totally unrelated to michael cohen - to run, especially now.

you can use the information provided below as you want. please note that i might have commited some copyright violations, though.

happy holidays - during these blasphemous times there is really no reason to talk about christmas. it's only irony eternally repeating itself that it's the hypocritical and immoral judeo-christian church militant that is killing the common god this time - they just couldn't wait for ai to do the job, could they?

all the best from finland, stay safe and take care!

text:
to women who have been abused and choose not to speak up... we honor you.
we remind you that there is no pressure for you to share your story.
only speak up about your abuse if it is safe.
.
if you are in a situation where sharing your story may put you in danger, it is wise to wait until you find a time or a person to share with, where you do feel safe.
.
and remember, sister... you are not alone.
women all over the world have been stepping up and saying #metoo.
the movement is not a passing fad.
this movement is going to keep moving like a wave of deep, soulful feminine healing.
let it move in you, even if you know it isn't time to raise your voice.
take solace knowing that your time will come, and you are not forgotten.
you are held in the hearts of so many women.
we believe in you, and in your resilient, wise, aching heart.
we are transforming ourselves to transform the world.
and we support you fully in your own process.
.
do you want to be supported by a private group of 50,000 women?
our facebook group is a safe space for you, and we welcome you with open arms.
click the link in our bio to join.
name: The Global Sisterhood
tweet_full:
to women who have been abused and choose not to speak up... we honor you.
we remind you that there is no pressure for you to share your story.
only speak up about your abuse if it is safe.
.
if you are in a situation where sharing your story may put you in danger, it is wise to wait until you find a time or a person to share with, where you do feel safe.
.
and remember, sister... you are not alone.
women all over the world have been stepping up and saying #metoo.
the movement is not a passing fad.
this movement is going to keep moving like a wave of deep, soulful feminine healing.
let it move in you, even if you know it is not time to raise your voice.
take solace knowing that your time will come, and you are not forgotten.
you are held in the hearts of so many women.
we believe in you, and in your resilient, wise, aching heart.
we are transforming ourselves to transform the world.
and we support you fully in your own process.
.
do you want to be supported by a private group of 50,000 women?
our facebook group is a safe space for you, and we welcome you with open arms.
click the link in our bio to join.

people who matter have listened in. üî¥

text:
better  be good

some of me is better when it's wild
he loves that too
my wild is me too
my dark is me too
my dance and my anger and my joy is
me too
me too

but for me, for us
for my little girl me
who finally gets to see she can be cared for
without abandonment
even during wild abandon

as long as i keep her safe
as long as he knows he's precious
as long as i am celebrating 
this singular, divine form
the sole experience of this body
this soul experience in this body
her too, is better
.
.
.
.

text:
yesterday would go down in the history of nigerian feminism as a day that witnessed women saying enough to the sexual harrassment of women in the marketplace. 
we at as equals africa are very proud of one of our members (damilola marcus) for creating the much needed market march organization which aims to protest against the normalized bullying and harrasment of women in markets. 
it is very necessary because if women are not comfortable in the market which is the most public of places, it says a lot about how we view women's mobility. 
market march however needs all the support it can get especially financially. so follow them on twitter @marketmarch and dami @omogedami. well done dami!!!
.
.
.
#marketmarch2018 #marketmarchyaba #marketmarch #sexualharrassment #abuse #metoo #bullying

text:
it's a yung pueblo kind of week. his healing words soothe my soul, relieve the tightness in my chest, release the tension in my muscles & have me bowing my head in agreement and gratitude. üôèüèΩ the end of mercury retrograde brought with it more asthma, tied to old wounds to feel and go/grow through. more instances of anxiety popping up that i could instantly acknowledge and be aware of and watch pass as i spoke through what feelings & thoughts were coming up. many of these feelings tied to my old career and the overwhelming stress which increased when i shifted to working corporate. 
how many of you have felt the following? you're just another face, "bosses" not even knowing what you did in your role but would politically thank you for your commitment and "everything" you do, fierce competition, only about the numbers game, feeling torn between helping the little guy but in doing so foregoing greater income and monthly quotas, not feeling appreciated by your bosses or those in your department, feeling like you're never doing enough/being enough/good enough, not really sure of who has your back or who  is your "friend," maybe even enduring #metoo vibes. and that's not all the guilt that comes from working and spending less time with your family and your kids.
üòë

just writing that all out & my current asthma episode has gone away & the tears well up. healing tears.
üò™

healing is quite the journey. it is not just love and light. it is looking within at our darkness and giving it the attention it needs to move through and transmute into the light. i have become more introverted in my healing. i am more conscious of who and what i give my time, my energy, my meness to. i protect myself better, i love myself more and not only on the outside or based on the labels i wear or the makeup i wear. i see the truth without a veil of what i wish to see. i say what needs to be said and hold my tongue when that is best.

yet i'm still healing. holding space for myself. taking more time to eat well, sleep more, pray more, laugh more, help more, love more, be grateful more, be open &  direct more, empathize more, be more non-judgmental, gossip less, worry less, anger less.

i felt togetherness, honesty, truth, empowerment and just blessed for tonya williams to get everyone together to speak their truth. it‚Äôs wonderful to know you have an army of wonderful women to your left and right and your not in it by yourself as i‚Äôve often felt. events like these brings about a chance to be together and address issues that matter to us in a transparent way, such as sexual harassment which runs way too rampant for my liking, inclusion which i cannot believe we are still battling in 2018 and for our voices to be heard in a meaningful way. this day was such an honour. good food and good conversation, who could ask for anything more?üå∑.

text:
pernah kah kau merasakan bahwa kau ingin menghadap pemilik kehidupan, tetapi tidak tahu mau berkata apa? kau hanya bisa menangis.
.
yah. saat itu kau ingin mengatakan banyak hal, tetapi tertahan. kau ingin protes, tetapi tidak layak. kau ingin marah tetapi tidak berhak. 
kau ingin menanyakan pertanyaan yang selama ini tidak pernah terjawab "mengapa aku?" "mengapa sakit sekali?"
"mengapa hal itu terjadi?"
lalu orang berkata bahwa semua itu ada alasan dan tujuannya. coba katakan pada ku apa alasan anak kecil berusia 5 tahun itu diperkosa. tujuannya apa? ketika sepanjang hidupnya dia trauma. ketika penyakit menggerogoti tubuhnya setelah nya. ketika kehidupannya sangat menderita setelah nya.
.
saat sangat terpuruk, satu-satunya yang kau inginkan adalah agar pemilik kehidupan itu mengambil kehidupan itu dari dirimu.
ketika rasa sakit itu terus menerus kau rasakan. ketika kau bangun pada rasa sakit yang sama setiap pagi. ketika malam hari kau tidur dengan mimpi buruk diperkosa. ketika siang hari kau menahan sakit fisik yang teramat sakit. kau sakit dengan berbagai penyakit. kau menderita siang dan malam selama berbulan-bulan. lalu, kau ingin mengakhiri penderitaan itu. karena kau sudah lelah bertahan. karena kau sudah terlalu kuat sejak puluhan tahun. 
masih sanggupkah aku mengatakan bahwa kau egois? masih sanggup kah aku mengatakan kalau kau sedang berdrama? 
lalu aku mengatakan mu kurang iman. sementara yang kau rasakan adalah bahwa tuhan sangat jauh. karena kau telah berulangkali dan terus menerus memanggilnya. tetapi pemilik kehidupan itu sepertinya diam dan kekuatan mu semakin memudar.
#womanquotes #greatwoman #saynotorapeculture #beboldwoman #perempuantangguh #greatwoman #depresi #korbanpemerkosaan #pemerkosaan #lukabatin #perempuanindonesia #ayah #ibu #remaja #perlindungananak #breakthesilent #bersuara #keadilanbagiperempuan #pejuang #petarung #metoo #dearlord #pituitarytumor #cancersurvivor #rapesurvivor

again, we know the reality, but let‚Äôs direct our energy appropriately, effectively.

it is the people you know, your brothers, friends, fathers, uncles, not animals.
keeping quiet makes you part of the problem.
times up!

text:
as we continue to see more women die at the hands of their partners, including just this weekend, it's crucial more effort is put into dismantling toxic masculinity.

which is why tsf's brianna and joe delivered a workshop on respectful relationships at a juvenile justice centre for boys in sydney this month.

brianna said "it was a challenging yet rewarding couple of days as we looked at what it means to be a man and how we can have better relationships with family, friends and lovers."

text:
it is so tempting to push down and turn away from uncomfortable emotions. as a result, so many of us have never learned or had the opportunity opportunity to experience an emotional state in a way that feels safe. cutting yourself off from one emotion can result the numbing of other feelings as well, even the ‚Äúgood‚Äù ones.
.
we are designed, as human beings, to experience a wide and richly diverse range of emotions, ‚Äúi withhold not my heart from any joy, for my heart rejoices in all my labor.‚Äù
.
for survivors of trauma, learning to confront feelings can be a challenging process. the key is understanding, finding support and techniques that can help navigate the fear. it is hard but rewarding work that can lead to a deeper wholeness and a richer experience of what it is to be human.
.

text: this record by @softcellhq blew my mind in 1981! i was 12 and had no idea what a lot of the titles of the trax & lyrics & sound fx meant.. but i knew i would go to #soho london & find out!  37 years later, 17 years #sober, i‚Äôm still finding out!! being #intersex and full of body shame i ‚Äòacted in‚Äô instead of out- most of my adult life i compulsively avoided emotional, intimate & sexual connection. the 12 step fellowship #slaa (sex & love addicts anonymous) calls this #sexual #anorexia. i found this to be a profoundly helpful term for me personally & as an addictions therapist. when i was in active addiction it took a lot of alcohol & other drugs for my body shame & dysmorphia to be quietened enough for me to be sexual. being with women felt safer (not always), i had childhood & adult sexual trauma #metoo & was more comfortable giving than receiving. it took becoming 7 & they/their/them for my whole sexual being to come back on line. t-shots help. i have so much more understanding & compassion for male sexuality than i did on just estrogen. #testosterone is actually in all bodies- not just cis men- and it plays a part in all of our sex drives. a lot of t makes regular sex a necessity - like food & water. patriarchy & the sexual control of women‚Äôs fertility (to pass on property & genes) is detrimental to men too. liberated women are much more fun & freer than those of us still bearing the heavy chains of our oppression. personally i refuse to fit into any boxes now. and as long as i‚Äôm safe, respectful of others boundaries & honoring the divinity of my body temple & sexuality, what the fuck has it got to do with anyone else? ps there is a very pro-monogamy, heterosexist model of sexuality & ‚Äòhealthy relationships‚Äô that can be quite shaming in some people‚Äôs model of #recovery. and apps can really feed into addiction with their exciting sound fx and promise of instant cock etc on demand. i am working with my support structure including v experienced therapist to ensure my mental & emotional safety too! i‚Äôm not closed to committed loving relationship but as i‚Äôm still getting divorced, that‚Äôs not where my head/heart or xl clit are at! #justsaying #honesty

text:
stereotypes. we live in a world that is full of them. our society is so easily influenced and judgemental, which is what creates our everyday stereotypes. many people i'm sure grew up with the stereotype 'boys have to be strong and girls are the ones that are weak.' this is obviously not true, but society has made many of us believe it is. if we take a look at our media today we see men who are tall, muscular, fit, strong and "handsome" as society likes to call them. why can't we find a diverse group of men, why do they have to look like this? this is a stereotype. this is what people expect from a "real" man, and many men themselves look up to be like this. which isn't right. men get insecure when they can't fit in with this structure they're supposed to be, and sometimes try to force themselves to get into it. they get into bad habits and eating disorders, that they are so driven to achieve. about 17% of men are on extreme diets, while 3% binge eat. binge eating is when you over eat. they do this because they feel they're too skinny, and need to gain more weight to grow muscles. 4% purge after eating, which adds on to the fact that 1 in 10 men have anorexia. however 3% also use performance enhancing drugs, starting at an adolescent age. why do these men and boys put themselves through such dangerous measures, just to be someone they're not. we need to help them understand they can be themselves and still be men. -

text:
one of the highlights of the last crazy busy weeks. it was a big pleasure to moderate the pes women annual conference on violence against women in politics, in lisbon, with great speakers, experts and activists. 
through a productive and lively discussion, we discussed the state of play, causes and consequences, we raised awareness and we moved the debates towards clear proposals on strategies and tools to combat it but also to change our political culture.

physical violence is just the tip of iceberg. ‚Äúviolence‚Äù is a much larger and complex concept. it is still a hidden phenomenon and one of the reasons why women still remain underrepresented, one of the main obstacles to the full participation of women in politics. 
recognizing the existence of the problem, naming it and breaking the silence about is the first necessary step to find effective solutions. 
#vaw #notthecost #progressiveeurope #metoo

video recordings available here: 
https://www.facebook.com/pes.women/videos/459604667902216/
https://www.facebook.com/pes.women/videos/2195192337406479/

text:
transformation ~ when you start to take care of you - really take care of you, you begin to see the changes.  it doesn‚Äôt happen overnight and it does take time. 
although i initially hesitated for a second or two, i knew signing up to work with my coach was what i needed.  i wouldn‚Äôt be where i‚Äôm at if i hadn‚Äôt. have you asked yourself what it is that you really need? 
if you are tired of your life as it is and want to make a change, then this might be your time for your transformation.  it is never too late to improve our lives, be happy with our choices and ourselves, and be on the path to making our goals and dreams actually real.  we can want it all we want, but until we begin the work to get there, it‚Äôs only a dream.  let‚Äôs make it our reality. 
what is it that you want your life to look like?  click on the link in my bio ‚û°Ô∏è @denisestyer to schedule a call with me.  we can discuss what it is you are looking for and how we might work together to make it happen. ¬†the really neat thing is that as long as you have internet, we can work together.  i love working with women and watching the transformation unfold! üêõü¶ãüíú

text:
i was diagnosed with complex ptsd over 10 years ago. i felt the healthcare system was too broken to help me heal and restore me to a state of being whole again. .
.
i was shamed, labeled, and extremely discriminated against, and revictimized by the family courts and untrained police, advocates and more. they perpetuated the abuse i was attempting to flea from for 13yrs. .
.
i discovered my savior was realigning with my soul and spirit which further led to the discovery of how to reclaim my life, heal, and restore wholeness. .
.
discovering these and seeing how they helped me in ways to heal the broken me the medical system failed me by numbing me with pharmaceuticals that did nothing for me to heal me but feel numb.

it is possible. what happened to you does not have to be a life sentence. .
.
i am walking proof. .
.
together we can break the stigma

break the cycle of abuse through healing. 
are you with me?

with love and appreciation, 
laura
@laura_healing_with_spirit 
www.laurahealingwithspirit.com .
.
.
.
.
.

text: we all have been caught in the down pour. proverbial or literal. you can hunch down and complain about the rain, how horrible it is, etc. or you can realize it's temporary, necessary and if you turn you can see the rainbow form. if you don't raise your head you won't ever see it. it's a -choice-. we can choose how we tackle the down pours of life. what we do afterwards. there was a time, i would of argued that. till i had my moment of clarity. when i realized it was in my hands, the world changed. no, it didn't become flowers and bunnies and sugar. but my out look became one of "i can do this" instead of "i cant". i raise my face into the rain and turn so i can see that first tint of a rainbow come alive...by my hand, in -my- life, from -my- work. i will be the light that will make that rainbow in my world and -nothing- from my past will change that. you...can do the same. üåà#selflove #selfcare #selfdiscovery #wellbeing #wellness #jusssayin #narcissist #narcissisticabuse #narcissism #metoo #abuse #crazymaking #traumabonding #emotionalabuse #toxicrelationships #survivor #gaslighting #toxicpeople¬† #mentalhealthawareness #domesticviolence #believewomen #ifmywoundswerevisible #dontlookback #narcissisticabusesurvivor

text:
a senior woman lawyer says the industry is changing because of the me too movement but not for the right reasons, in the first part of a rnz series katie scotcher looks at how #metoo gained momentum in new zealand.

law firms had their #metoo moment when interns at the law firm russell mcveagh complained about being sexually assaulted by senior lawyers - an investigation found a culture of excessive drinking - and that the complaints had been poorly managed.

the lawyer, who rnz has agreed not to name, has found law firms are starting to move away from a "work hard, play hard" culture but she questions what is motivating the change.
.
"the firms are now a lot more scared of that kind of thing happening because if it is made public they can see what the ramifications are and that it can have a real impact on the business.

text:
i was excited about getting this book on loan - i had heard bri briefly explaining the premise, and i thought it would be a vital read. when i finally got it, i discovered i had to work up towards it, almost bracing myself. this terrible feeling in my gut, my reluctance to learn about how rampant sexual assault is in the community around us, only serves to highlight how courageous bri lee is in putting together this account.

bri shares her experiences as a judge's associate, dealing with a disconcerting number of sexual assault cases, often perpetrated on victims young enough to be held on our laps as children. she then made the decision to file a complaint against someone who had assaulted her when she was younger.

eggshell skull is incredibly readable given the subject matter that it deals with. it is informative and brilliantly written. and above all, it should be commended as an act of standing up for what is right, not only for the person wronged, but for every other 'her' - and indeed, 'him' - living through episodes of violation, fearing that the scales of justice will not tip in their favour. 
#eggshellskull #brilee #aussieauthors #reading #memoir #narrativenonfiction #metoo @bri.e.lee @allenandunwin

text:
tw: sexual assault
tiffany mason was just a teenager when she decided to dedicate her life to figure skating. she left her family and moved hours away to live and train with an elite coach, hoping to one day represent the united states and the philippines in the olympics. the training was rigorous, but the other challenges she faced posed a more serious problem. after just a few months her coach's husband began sexually abusing her.
i was 18. he knew it was the first time away from my parents, and that i was dedicated to skating above all else. he gained my trust, and then he violated it,‚Äù remembers tiffany. the coach‚Äôs husband isolated tiffany from her

friends, family, and coach, and he repeatedly threatened her not to speak out. ‚Äúhe told me that if i said anything, my skating career would go out the window. skating was really important to me‚Äîand i believed him. so i kept my mouth shut.‚Äù
tiffany tried to focus her energy on skating, but the stress of keeping it inside affected her physical and mental health. ‚Äúi would come home from practice and turn off the lights and sleep until dinner. i felt depressed. i felt terrible.‚Äù eventually she reached out to a friend who lived in new york city, but his reaction was unsupportive. ‚Äúhe told me to ‚Äòjust leave.‚Äô he didn‚Äôt really get it, and it just pushed me back even further.‚Äù
a year after leaving home, tiffany visited her parents for the holidays. they noticed that her weight, mental health, and skating performance had declined, and they decided she would not return to live with her coach. once the decision was made, she talked to her parents about what happened, but again she was met with disbelief. ‚Äúthey didn‚Äôt believe me. they said, ‚Äòif this really happened why didn‚Äôt you say anything about it? i can‚Äôt believe he would do something like this.‚Äô‚Äù

text:
"power is not given to you. you have to take it." - beyonc√©
.
one of our high school teachers recently invited my sister and i to come converse with his class about our experiences as females out in the real world. so for the past few weeks, i've been intensely reflecting on how being female plays out when i'm at work, in the dynamic of my current relationship, and even in the simple choices i make, like whether or not i'm going to shave today...or why i even started shaving in the first place ü§î (food for thought!) i don't think i've come any closer to figuring out what it means to be female in today's society, but i have definitely learned a lot about myself by stopping to think about it.
.
after talking to some of my female friends, i was unsurprised that we all seemed to share some common experiences: being objectified, belittled, or even harrassed - while at work, walking across the street, or enjoying a night out. what did surprise me is that, even in this era of #metoo that is supposed to have us feeling all confident and empowered to stand up for ourselves, the truth is that when those things happen, most of us don't even react. for example, i personally let things go all the time when people make inappropriate comments, or jokes, or assumptions about my intellligence. not proud of it, but i've even laughed along half-heartedly, not feeling quick-witted enough to have a comeback.  truth is, my automatic response to most situations, especially fleeting ones, is to be polite...only to smh seconds after and wonder why i just ok'd their sexism by staying silent ü§¶ now if that's not a picture of powerlessness, i don't know what is. .

needless to say, i am super excited to have open and honest conversations about my experiences with the kiddos, and learn what they have to say about all this. because #metoo, and #feminism in general, only work if we feel just as confident speaking up before things happen, and when they happen, so hopefully they stop happening altogether üôè #sorryfortherant #inmyfeelings #goodnightworld .
.

for all the people have been abused in their vessel
i love you.
i see you.
i feel you.
if you have been touched beyond your will..
if you have felt unsafe within the walls of your own home..
if you shrink in fear at the thought of another..
if ‚Äòno‚Äô wasn‚Äôt enough even after pleading..
i love you.
i see you.
i feel you.
abuse is not okay.
in any form.
by anyone.
the second abuse shows up
you get up and leave
and if you can‚Äôt, you scream. 
it is not to be tolerated.
you are worth so much more than that.
i know it‚Äôs often easier to stay silent but this is not the time.
be silent no more
for this is your vessel
your light and your home.
be silent no more
for he (or she) cannot touch you¬†
in your safe abode.
be silent no more
for you came here not to suffer
or be a toy for the hurting.
be silent no more.
your voice is your strength

text:
lawyer questions law firms‚Äô motivation for changes after #metoo
#
a senior woman lawyer says the industry is changing because of the me too movement but not for the right reasons, in the first part of a rnz series katie scotcher looks at how #metoo gained momentum in new zealand. photo: 123rf law firms had their #metoo moment when interns at the law firm russell mcveagh complained about being sexually assaulted by senior lawyers - an investigation found a culture of excessive drinking - and that the complaints had been poorly managed. the lawyer, who rnz has agreed not to name, has found law firms are starting to move away from a "work hard, play hard" culture but she questions what is motivating the change. "the firms are now a lot more scared of that kind of thing happening because if it is made public they can see what the ramifications are and that it can have a real impact on the business. "law firms are financial beasts and we're only going to see real genuine change if there's a financial implication for the firm when these things come out. and that's only really going to happen if clients stand up and say this is unacceptable," she said. an intern‚Ä¶

text:
raven, #a063586, female, 1 year old
raven is fun, fun, fun!! she is a kitten trapped in a big cat's body, and she's a large cat at that. she is outgoing, confident, and friendly. this active girl loves batting around kitty toys and interacting with you. she also has an incredibly sweet side and turns into a little purr box when you love on her. raven has a gorgeous shiny black coat and lovely pale green eyes. she also has a talkative side and likes to be a part of whatever it is you're doing at the moment, whether you need the help or not. she is sure to bring entertainment and bliss to her new family. please consider her.

kurth memorial animal services & adoption center
1901 hill st., lufkin, tx
phone: (936) 633-0218
open mon-sat 10am-4:45pm (closed sundays and major holidays)
adoption fee is waived with a donation of $20 or more to the vetting fund from november 13th-january 5th for the home fur the howlidays adoption special (regularly $60), which includes initial vaccination, deworming, wellness coupon, & spay/neuter surgery

text:
‚Äútime‚Äôs up‚Äù - acrylic on canvas 
new work for the #45series. 30‚Äùx24‚Äù
addressing the women‚Äôs right to be heard in all manners of life. i was inspired by an article from @thecut during the #kavanaughhearings. 
for centuries she has only been able to listen (hence the ear peeking out), not speak. mixing the medieval ‚Äúscold bridle‚Äù device, that was used as a punishment for being too chiding and annoying, with a 21st century woman wearing @alexandermcqueen  shows that even today women are struggling to be heard. additionally the objectification of women is juxtaposed with the strength and fight to speak up- including women owning their sexuality .
this painting is quite personal to me in many ways, so i dressed her in one of my favorite designers and added one or two of my features.
#timesup #metoo #believesurvivors 
#speakup #scoldbridle #alexandermcqueen #painting #art #acrylic #canvas

text:
"gizarte honen erronka da babes handiagoa eskaintzea indarkeriaren biktima diren emakumeei, haren aurka borrokatzen ari direnei eta haien seme-alabei, eta erantzukizuna itzultzea erasotzaileei eta haiek matxismoan sozializatu dituen gizarte bati. geure buruari galdetu behar diogu zer dela-eta pentsatzen duten zenbait gizonek beren bikotekideak umiliatzeko, irrigarri uzteko, haiei oihukatzeko, errespeturik gabe tratatzeko, erasotzeko edota hiltzeko eskubidea dutela; zer dela-eta sentitzen duten zenbait gizonek kalean emakume bati eraso egiteko eskubidea dutela, edo haien espazioan sartzeko edo nagusitasun-egoera batez baliatuz haiez abusatzeko eskubidea dutela. zenbait gizonek emakumeei eraso egiten badiete, hori egin dezaketela sentitzen dutelako da. emakumeak ez badira horrelako indarkeriazko harremanetatik ateratzen, sarritan ezin dutelako da. utz diezaiogun erantzukizun guztia haien bizkar gainean jartzeari, utz diezaiogun geure buruari galdetzeari ea emakume horiek beren egoera salatu zuten ala ez, utz diezaiogun haien hitza zalantzan jartzeari, utz diezaiogun beren egoera dela-eta emakume horiek lotsarazteari. balia dezagun berdintasun-olatu hau, egoera lazgarri hau aldatzeko" izaskun landaida

text:
hari yang luar biasa dalam hidup kami, bertemu sosok guru yang luar biasa hebat.
beliau akrab kami panggil pak zam.

banyak hal yang kami peroleh dari beliau tentang apa arti cerdas yang sesungguhnya. cerdas bukan hanya tentang intelektual, bukan hanya tentang nilaimu 100. bukan hanya itu, seseorang dikatakan cerdas bukan karena itu tapi karena lebih dari itu yakni adanya keseimbangan antara intelektual, spiritual, dan emosional. cerdas intelektual saja tidak menjamin kita sukses. dengan sebuah cerita beliau memahamkan kami bahwa kecerdasan emosi juga sangat penting. selain itu juga butuh spiritual yang baik karena apa? karena kalau tanpa ilmu agama maka yang dilakukan tersebut akan menjadi sia sia

beliau juga menjelaskan kepada kami tentang nilai nilai keteladanan di sma 1 yogyakarta, nilai itu haruslah tetap ada dan harus diwariskan kepada angkatan selanjutnya.

teladan bukanlah segalanya, tapi segalanya bisa berawal dari bumi teladan

text:
real talk: 
ptsd fucking sucks. there are days where i feel normal and functional, maybe even happy and then some random trigger happens and suddenly, my reality becomes fractured, the boundaries between past and present blurred nearly into oblivion and nothing is ok, nothing is safe. especially at night. nighttime in particular is terrifying for me. i haven't had my nightmare medication for the last 4 nights which has resulted in several nights of me hyperventilating, sobbing uncontrollably, shaking in terror from the images and memories running through my mind. 
i do not have the words to adequately describe how grateful i am for my network of supportive friends. many of these beautiful souls have sat up with me, repeating over and over that i'm safe, holding me until the spell of terror has passed. 
of course the worst part about having these flashbacks and panic attacks is the overwhelming feeling of guilt for needing support, the frustration and self hatred that i can't just "get over it" and the intrusive voice of perpetrators repeating "it's all in your head, you're making it up" 
it's enough to drive you insane.
but to all my fellow ptsd survivors out there please hear me when i say this: 
it is not your fault
you didn't deserve it.
it's not in your head.
your feelings are valid. 
you are not a burden. 
you will get through this. 
and i am proud of you for anyything and everything healthy and constructive you've been able to get done today.

text:
for a country as liberal as the usa when it comes to free speech - australia‚Äôs defamation laws can seem quite scary to the average american.

it‚Äôs no wonder that our recent defamation cases, especially when there are echoes of the #metoo movement involved, are making headlines in the states.

actor geoffrey rush took on the daily telegraph earlier this year over published articles he considered defamatory (no final decision has been made on this case yet - judgment will be handed down early next year). the articles reported that a fellow actor had lodged a complaint with the sydney theatre company over alleged ‚Äúinappropriate behaviour‚Äù who was later revealed to be eryn jean torvill. 
today, australian actor @yaelstone, who is most well known for her role as lorna morello in orange is the new black, has shared her experiences of working with geoffrey rush. her allegations include that he danced naked in front of her in their shared dressing room, used a mirror to watch her while she showered and sent her occasionally erotic text messages while they starred together in ‚Äúthe diary of a madman‚Äù in 2010 and 2011.

in her interview published by the new york times, she details those allegations as well as her fear about speaking out amidst australia‚Äôs defamation laws. she said had a law firm not volunteered to represent her pro bono, she wouldn‚Äôt have been able to come forward.

head to @nytimes to read the article in full.

text:
muchas mujeres correntinas nos juntamos en la legislatura por semanas para exigir #paridad...
pedimos que la envien en extraordinarias.
le pedimos a la oposicion que negocie. que se juegue.
nos forrearon hasta el final. tibieza de todos.
nos dijeron que nos falto estrategia.
nos dijeron q tenian q estudiar..(4 proyectos tenian, uno enviado por el p.e., otros desde febrero)
nos dijeron que era un dcho natural..
que no la necesitabamos...
que solo necesitabamos capacidad e idoneidad 
que no habia mujeres para cubrir las listas.
una mujer nos grito que jamas votaria esa ley.
un senador antes gobernador prohibio el ingreso en la ultima sesion de vs chicas del colectivo por la paridad.
lisa y llanamente en corrientes nos invisibilizaron y negaron un dcho.
y eso fue violencia institucional ademas....
una chica, apoyada por la colectiva de mujeres actrices se para frente a un microfono, denuncia que otro actor la violo hace 9 a√±os.. empiezan las denuncias... empiezan los escraches...
se cagan todos
y meten en extraordinarias el proyecto de ley micaela.
y macri lanza el piod.
plan nacional de igualdad y derechos.
se dan cuenta que estos tipos son hijos del rigor?
y en corrientes?
se dan cuenta que 17 a√±os en el poder los volvio insensibles y bestias?
se dan cuenta que necesitamos un #metoo?
tenemos funcionarios denunciados x violencia de genero..y los protegen.
tipos que corrieron a una mina con una trincheta....colombi le dijo..no vengas x unos dias..cajonearon la denuncia..y lo premian con vs cargos consecutivos..ahora el tipo representa legalmente al estado como si nada.
funcionarios que dejaron a sus mujeres en estado casi vegetativo...y siguen..todos lo saben..te lo dicen por lo bajo y lo protegen.
acosadores seriales por doquier...y siguen incolumes por la vida como si fuera un dcho natural...
para ellos lo es.
hijos no reconocidos y nada...les tiran unos mangos por izquierda o se bancan juicios ...
o que se los imputen aun negandose al adn y llegan a cargos "supremos".
hacen un culto del levante para que las minas ocupen cargos..y no pasa nada...
golpean a mujeres..y tampoco pasa nada.
ergo.... se dan cuenta que estos tipos son hijos del rigor y estan necesitando

text:
a three-year-old indian girl is in critical condition after she was allegedly raped by her neighbour in the capital delhi.

the accused, a 40-year-old security guard who worked in the building the child lived in, has been arrested.

police found the girl unconscious and rushed her to hospital where she is undergoing surgery.

the incident occurred on sunday, which was the sixth anniversary of the brutal gang rape of a student on a delhi bus.

text:
*dear nation*

dear nation,
it's been six years since you mourned for a girl who lost her life to monsters. you called her every synonym of courage you could find in a thesaurus. you spilled on the streets, screaming for justice. you promised the little girls clenching their tiny hands that it won't happen again. in the same rally, someone groped a girl and you didn't let rage roll down your lips. instead you questioned her character, asking what she was doing so late at night.

dear nation,
a three-year-old gets raped six years later on the same day and you are busy tweeting about celeb marriages. you file firs against comedians because jokes make your blood boil, but crimes against women of this country never do. i wonder what kind of chemistry your body follows!

you buy a smart phone and an internet connection, only to dismiss all the #metoo stories, calling the survivors whores and attention seekers.

you rant about your worries regarding the safety of women but you never question your sons when they mistreat them. you make promises only to break them. you always check whether the rapist is underage and let him go if he is, because children make mistakes and they need to be forgiven. 
but what about those who are punished for the deeds they never committed? i wonder where your sympathy hides when it comes to the survivors, and why it only shows up for the underage rapists.

dear nation,
you will once again spill on the streets, like you did six years ago, seeking justice. but this time too, you won't find it. or will you? ~ dishita kaushik (@_dishita01_)

in my eyes, the dairy industry may just be the worst in the world. ‚†Ä
so many people still consume dairy (i did for such a long time) without realising what actually goes on behind the 'happy cows' that you see in all the advertisements. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
mother cows are raped by humans and impregnated multiple times throughout their life to keep them almost always lactating. their babies are taken from them which has been proven to absolutely destroy them emotionally and leaves them in a state of fear. they're enslaved for years just for their milk, and then murdered when they're not useful anymore. oh, and did i mention what happens to all of their babies that aren't female... they're either left to die (it's not illegal in australia to neglect a farm animal in the first week of it's life), or they're sent off to be made into veal.
.

text: the last few days has been a whirlwind to say the least. immediately following my fight, i was back in philly bright and early (too early üò≠), to film my scenes for the music video for @rozessounds new amazing single, halfway there.  over the two days of filming, i  was moved to tears on more than one occasion... the song not only hits  home for me, but for so many women who are silently fighting a battle that no one knows about. i am proud that i could  to be a strong presence and another voice for these women. you are not alone. ever. i am so blessed to share so many amazing moments like these with my daughter who is truly beyond strong, confident, and empowered in her own right. a true force to be reckoned with!  after 2 days of filming we wrapped our day with one last interview at home with our wonderful friends for @thefloatfilm! i cannot wait for this film to be released to #netflix in summer 2019! #abundantlyblessed #metoo #girlpower #womensupportingwomen #womeninsports #strongertogether #thefloatfilm #shanestott

text:
this is a tribute to a person who even don't know more about me, 
who even don't meet to me till now, 
who even don't know the address of my house,

text:
lots of people have asked me how i did it.  how on earth did i lose 145 lbs?

i got sober.  i stopped drinking 5000 calories a day.  i stopped getting up in the middle of the night and eating bags of cookies.  i found a great nutritionist.  i followed the bulletproof diet.  i got really active.  i followed viome.  other than viome i had done all those things before and everything i lost i gained back. 
you know what really made the difference? 
purpose.  and healing. 
cuz all the mindset work and low carb diets in the world will only be a coping strategy until we uncover the reason that we‚Äôre here.  and heal.  heal all the reasons i coped with famous amos cookies gin, wine and beer. 
heal all the reasons i was hiding and protecting.  heal all the reasons i needed to be invisible and not seen. 
i remember saying that gluten and alcohol and sugar wouldn‚Äôt be on this planet if we weren‚Äôt meant to enjoy them.  maybe, but having peeled back the layers and healing i now know what works for my body and what doesn‚Äôt. 
so the secret isn‚Äôt keto or bulletproof or sobriety though all those things propelled me forward.  it‚Äôs healing. 
i‚Äôm not a health coach or a weight loss coach, but finding and embracing purpose makes a difference in every area of your life.  just sayin üòâ

and if i did it, anyone can.  really. 
when you‚Äôre ready to have this be the year to find your purpose, heal your relationships, bring in epic love and a community that supports you- i‚Äôm here.

text:
now that you have a sense of the interlocking dynamics of degradation, isolation and intimidation, i hope it is easier to empathize with the plight of a victim. perhaps you are already aware of how your efforts could work at cross purposes with her situation. ¬∂

coercive control is when a man who does not practice equality attempts to have his historical entitlements as a man met by a partner or previous partner (entitlements to care-taking, to sex, to being an authority, to doing less than half his share in the relationship/home, and so on.) because of this, your role as a bystander is both to support the victim and to do so by opposite means. the abuser takes control. you eschew controlling her. the abuser holds her to impossible, contradictory standards. you accept her complex situation. the abuser is more ‚Äúlogical‚Äù and ‚Äúreasonable‚Äù than her. you respect her intuitive assessment of her risks, needs, capacities and timing. ¬∂

the abuser is ‚Äújust trying to help‚Äù her. you are empowering her. ¬∂

it‚Äôs important to be aware of yourself. do you feel urgency or danger? that‚Äôs rational. consider safety measures for yourself and offer them to the victim. do you feel frustrated with her? assume there is something she cannot articulate to you that you would also find paralyzing. are you focusing your efforts on her like a pawn you can move? she is already carrying the burden of the abuser‚Äôs behavior because he blames his actions on her. ¬∂

the tough part is you cannot be neutral with him. your job is not to be morally indifferent because she is experiencing a human rights violation (many forms of intimate partner abuse when perpetrated against a stranger are *crimes.*) simultaneously, she is a whole human being. she may resist the abuse in ways you don‚Äôt approve of. it‚Äôs important not to over-idealize victims or require them to be perfect both because it leads to burn-out and perpetuates the problem. you are empowering her and that may mean she has the power to make bad choices. you are a champion of her humanity not another unrealistic vision of femininity.
name: CleverLeigh

text:
in scar tissue, best friends jessica and sam each have scars from their pasts that have never quite healed. jessica has never been able to get passed an extremely damaging romantic relationship from her formative years in college, while sam has been ignoring a painfully fractured relationship with her sister. after years of denial, an impromptu lunch date and a surprise overnight guest force them both to confront these wounds and face what they didn‚Äôt want to see head on. scar tissue is a poignant look into what happens when we leave our carefully crafted realities and dive headfirst into the gray areas we repeatedly try to ignore.

text:
it's been a minute, booklovers! i can only blame the dreary weather my town tends to have. plus days getting shorter means less daylight for me to take pictures in, and with my job schedule, i'm home when it's already dark. but i had to somehow get around to posting my thoughts on this book, even if it wasn't my best picture set-up!
‚Ä¢
if you haven't read saints and misfits, i highly recommend it for reasons:
- diversity, first off! the mc is a muslim american teenage girl. and if you have had curiosity bubbling about general aspects of islam, you learn a great deal of information from this.
- incredibly important read for the #metoo movement. this book does deserve a tw for sexual assault, but the main focus of it is on what happens after. what do you do when your assaulter is actually a beloved member for a very close knit community??
‚Ä¢
i went into it thinking there would be lots of fluff but there is more heaviness to it than fluff although some parts brought about smiles, despite the topic. but anyone who has been in that position before (like myself) will find a great deal of familiarity and it might make you uncomfortable or angry (i was the latter). but i do hope this book manages to give someone strength!
‚Ä¢
